Lab 13 - Referer-Based Access Control
Objective
Exploit a broken access control vulnerability that relies on the HTTP Referer header to promote the low-privileged user (wiener) to administrator.

Background
The application provides an administrative function for upgrading user roles.

Instead of verifying whether the authenticated user has administrative privileges, the application incorrectly relies on the HTTP Referer header to determine whether the request originated from the admin panel.

Vulnerability
Broken Access Control – Referer-Based Authorization

The server granted access to privileged functionality based on the client-controlled Referer header.

Because HTTP headers can be modified by an attacker, this authorization mechanism is insecure.

Reconnaissance
Logged in as:

administrator : admin
Observed the role upgrade request:

GET /admin-roles?username=carlos&action=upgrade
The request contained:

Referer: https://<lab-id>.web-security-academy.net/admin
This suggested that the application might be validating the Referer header instead of verifying the user's privileges.

Exploitation
Logged in as:

wiener : peter
Captured the administrator's request and modified:

Cookie:
↓

Wiener's session
Changed:

username=carlos
↓

username=wiener
Preserved:

Referer: https://<lab-id>.web-security-academy.net/admin
The server accepted the request and upgraded Wiener's account to administrator.

Why the Attack Worked
The application trusted the Referer header to determine whether the request originated from the administrative interface.

Since Referer is entirely controlled by the client, an attacker could forge the header using Burp Suite and bypass authorization.

